CAPE TOWN - This years’ Cape Wine Auction raised more than R12.2 million for charity, and has now accumulated over R117m since the first auction was held in 2014.Held in partnership with Mastercard at the luxurious Quoin Rock wine estate in Stellenbosch on Saturday, the auction saw guests bidding generously for a collection of once-in-a-lifetime lots.The day’s highest bid of R1.2m was for Lot 17, which included a three-night getaway for eight people in the Bazaruto Archipelago at &Beyond Benguerra Island, as well as return private charter flights from Cape Town or Johannesburg, and return scenic helicopter transfers from the lodge and Vilanculos. It was sponsored by Spier wine farm.Other fiercely-contested lots included the Best of British Lot 18: golf, horse racing and tickets to a Premier League football game; Lot 7: Celebrating Goodness with wine, dining and travel experiences in both South Africa and France; Lot 11: a celebration of South African excellence; and, Lot 14: a week’s stay in Tuscany.The Gift of the Giving Lots also raised a significant amount of money. These are straightforward donations to charitable causes, with no prize/holiday/experience in return, and consisted of five R10 000 donations, five of R25 000, five R50 000 donations and one of R100 000.The Cape Wine Auction is regarded as one of the most significant international wine charity auctions ever conducted in South Africa, uniting the industry around a single goal of raising money for education.The auction has created a benchmark in philanthropy, raising over R117m, with 100 percent of proceeds managed by the Cape Wine Auction Trust and distributed among carefully-selected beneficiaries in the Cape Winelands.“We are delighted with this year’s results, especially given the tough economic times we are going through. The monies raised means the Cape Wine Auction Trust can continue its invaluable work with our beneficiaries, all of whom are dedicated to improving the education and lives of children in the Cape winelands,” said Cape Wine Auction director Darielle Robertson.Cape Times